Aphasia

[!TIP] Mnemonic
WARped Banana

  • WA - wernicke's aphasia is Receptive (ie Broca's must be expressive), located Posteriorly

  • BaNana - Broca's aphasia is Non-Fluent (i.e Wernicke's must be Fluent), located Anteriorly

Receptive aphasia

Also called Wernicke's aphasia, Fluent Aphasia.

[!TIP] Receptive Aphasia:
Language looses meaning - The patient can't understand questions and words come tumbling out.
Words and their meaning are dissociated.


Source

Expressive Aphasia

[!TIP] Expressive Aphasia:
Meaning of language is preserved; The patient can understand questions and knows the 'meaning' of what he want's to say. But the words aren't there. "Tip of the tongue".
A 'disorder of expression'

Source
Broca's aphasia, Non-fluent Aphasia
Note: Mike has paralysis of his right hand -> i.e a left sided lesion

Broca's and Wernicke's areas

There is a language loop in the brain.

This language loop is found in the left hemisphere in about 90% of right-handed persons and 70% of left-handed persons. Source

The main components are Broca's area and Wernicke's area connected by the arcuate fasciculus.

  • Wernicke's area: Superior posterior temporal lobe
  • Broca's area: Posterior inferior frontal gyrus

Alzheimers disease

#2021GM-NOV Q01

Molecular basis

Transmembrane protein "Amyloid precursor protein" (APP) is broken down by two pathways.

  • BACE + gamma-secretase pathway -> produces Beta amyloid.
  • Alpha secretase + gamma secretase pathway -> produces harmless products.

Mutations in APP or gamma secretase increase the rate of formation of beta amyloid which causes Alzheimer's disease.

Beta amyloid accumulation is

  • directly toxic to neurons

  • Large deposits form Neuritic plaques elicit local inflammatory response.

  • Causes hyperphosphorylation of intracellular Tau protein.

    • Tau protein is a protein which stabilizes microtubules and regulates protein binding to microtubules in healthy cells.
    • Phosphorylation causes Tau protein to redistribute from axons to dendrites and cell bodies where it forms Neurofibrillary tangles which cause neuronal dysfunction and cell death.

  • So, plaques are extracellular and tangles are intracellular.

  • Neuritic plaques are collections of dystrophic neurites around a central amyloid core.

    • There is sparing of the primary motor and sensory cortices until the late stages.

  • Neurofibrillary tangles - intracellular accumulations of phosphorylated Tau protein. They are not specific to Alzheimer's dementia.

Genetic risk factors:

Risk is increased by:

  • Down syndrome (APP is on Chromosome 21)
  • Point mutations of APP gene.
  • E4 allele of apolipoprotein E gene
  • Presenilin 1 and 2 - mutations affect gamma secretase function.

other risk factors

Age, head trauma, vascular factors

Morphology

Cortical atrophy mainly in frontal, temporal and parietal lobes.
MRI -> changes visible first in mesial temporal lobe structures including hippocampi (hippocampus).
Early stage imaging may be normal.

[!INFO] Limbic System
Hippocambus:
Essentially the memory centre of our brains. Here, our episodic memories are formed and catalogued to be filed away in long-term storage across other parts of the cerebral cortex.
Amygdala : "almond like shape"
Located right next to the hippocampus, the left and right amygdalae play a central role in our emotional responses, including feelings like pleasure, fear, anxiety and anger. The amygdala also attaches emotional content to our memories, and so plays an important role in determining how robustly those memories are stored. Memories that have strong emotional meaning tend to stick.

Treatment of Alzheimer's dementia

Pathology of Alzheimers' disease

Most cases are sporadic. Only 5-10% are familial.

[!INFO] Tau protein

Tau protein is a protein found in diverse cells like amoebas, insects to humans. It regulated the binding of other proteins to the microtubules. Source and helps to stabilize the cytoskeleton of neurons.

Many neurodegenerative diseases are characterised by tangled proteins called Tau filbrils.

ARDS - acute respiratory distress syndrome

[!TIP] Summary (read this bit if you're in a hurry.)
ARDS is a syndrome of diffuse alveolar damage that occurs because of some systemic or pulmonary insult.
Some insult causes increased permeability of either the capillary endothelium or alveolar epithelium leading to diffuse alveolar oedema.
This oedema leads to intrapulmonary shunting and volutrauma and atelectrauma.
The rest are details

Definition:
Older definition: an acute condition characterized by bilateral pulmonary infiltrates and severe hypoxemia in the absence of evidence for cardiogenic pulmonary edema.

Newer definition:
A condition causing

  • bilateral opacities not explained by effusion, consolidation or atelectasis
  • Oedema not fully explained by cardiogenic causes
  • Onset within 1 week of clinical insult
  • hypoxaemia of differing severities as defined by P/F radio (at a PEEP of 5cm H2O)
    • 200 - 300 - Mild
    • 100 - 200 - Moderate
    • < 100 - Severe
    • The hypoxaemia is due to significant intrapulmonary shunting.

Pathophysiology:
Early exudative phase where alveoli fill with fluid due to increased capillary permeability.

Damage which triggers ARDS can be on either side of the alveolar-capillary membrane:

  • to the capillary endothelium (eg sepsis)
  • or the alveolar epithelium - (eg after aspiration)

On the alveolar side,
type II pneumocytes are more resistant to injury but damage to them results in loss of surfactant and alveolar collapse.
This causes some aveoli to collapse while others becomes overdistended (while on a ventilator).
ARDS facilitates further lung damage:

  • Overdistended alveoli undergo volutrauma.
  • The collapsed alveoli undergo cycles of collapse and expansion leading to atelectrauma. (i.e ARDS is an inhomogenous process)
  • These types of trauma promote secretion of proinflammatory cytokines.
  • Increased airway pressure during ventilation is associated with development of ARDS.

The use of positive end-expiratory pressure (PEEP) to diminish alveolar collapse and the use of low tidal volumes and limited levels of inspiratory filling pressures appear to be beneficial in diminishing the observed VAL

Causes of ARDS:

  • Sepsis
  • Trauma
  • Burns
  • Massive transfusion
  • Pneumonia
  • Aspiration
  • Near drowning
  • Post perfusion injury after Cardiopumonary bypass.
  • Pancreatitis
  • Fat embolism

Primary sclerosing cholangitis



Progressive and chronic liver disease caused by autoimmune mediated fibrosis of intra and extrahepatic bile ducts.
Often complicated by cholangiocarcinoma.
Treament is not curative; it's aimed at minimizing symptoms and managing complications.
Liver transplantation is the only treatment than can alter progression.
Affects young to middle aged males.
PSC without IBD is more likely to occur in women.
PSC is seen predominantly in non smokers.
Ix: AST, ALT, GGT all elevated. Fluctuating conjugated hyperbilirubinaemia.

hypergammaglobulinaemia is present.
Best imaging modality: MRCP
